from pyecharts.faker import Faker
from pyecharts import options as opts
from pyecharts.charts import Bar,Line

def overlap_line_scatter() -> Bar:
    x =  ["1996", "2000", "2009"]
    bar = (
        Bar()
        .add_xaxis(x)
        .add_yaxis("", ['243000000','259000000','310000000'])
        .set_global_opts(title_opts=opts.TitleOpts(title=""))
    )
    line = (
        Line()
        .add_xaxis(x)
        .add_yaxis("", ['263000000','282000000','307000000'])
    )
    bar.overlap(line)
    return bar

overlap_line_scatter().render_notebook()

from folium import plugins

# let's start again with a clean copy of the map of United State
san_map = folium.Map(location = [latitude, longitude], zoom_start = 4)

# instantiate a mark cluster object for the incidents in the dataframe
incidents = plugins.MarkerCluster().add_to(san_map)

# loop through the dataframe and add each data point to the mark cluster
for lat, lng, label, in zip(data.latitude, data.longitude, cdata1.Title):
    folium.Marker(
        location=[lat, lng],
        icon=None,
        popup=label,
    ).add_to(incidents)

# add incidents to map
san_map.add_child(incidents)

from flask import Flask, render_template, request
import pandas as pd

# ,     
import cufflinks as cf
import plotly as py
import plotly.graph_objs as go

app = Flask(__name__)

#  
# pandas , dropna(), unique(), 
df = pd.read_csv('Mass_nd.csv', encoding='ISO-8859-1', sep=',' )
regions_available_loaded = list(df.code.dropna().unique())

# cufflinks ploty, 
cf.set_config_file(offline=True, theme="ggplot")
py.offline.init_notebook_mode()


@app.route('/',methods=['GET'])
def hu_run_2019():

    data_str = df.to_html()  # pandas .to_html() !!  "Hello"
                             # pandas!
    
    regions_available = regions_available_loaded #
    return render_template('results2.html',
                           the_res = data_str,   # 
                           the_select_region=regions_available)   

@app.route('/hurun',methods=['POST'])
def hu_run_select() -> 'html':
    
    the_region = request.form["the_region_selected"]  ## 
    print(the_region)                                 ## , 

    dfs = df.query("code=='{}'".format(the_region)) ## df.query(). the_region

    data_str = dfs.to_html()  # dfs, 

    ## plot_all = "" # <------------------  , 
    ## 
    #

    fig = go.Figure(data=go.Choropleth(
        locations=dfs['code'], # Spatial coordinates
        z = dfs['total'].astype(float), # Data to be color-coded
        locationmode = 'USA-states', # set of locations match entries in `locations`
        colorscale = 'Reds',
        colorbar_title = "Millions USD",
    ))

    fig.update_layout(
        title_text = '',
        geo_scope='usa', # limite map scope to USA
    )

    fig.show()
    py.offline.plot(fig, filename=".html",auto_open=False) 
    
    with open(".html", encoding="utf8", mode="r") as f:                     # ".html"
        plot_all = "".join(f.readlines())
    
    regions_available =  regions_available_loaded #
    return render_template('results2.html',
                            the_plot_all = plot_all,
                            the_res = data_str,
                            the_select_region=regions_available,
                           )

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(port = 8005)   # debug=True, py, ipynb

import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib as mpl
import seaborn as sns
color = sns.color_palette()

%matplotlib inline

# Any results you write to the current directory are saved as output.

mass_shooting = pd.read_csv('Mass.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1", parse_dates=["Date"])

mass_shooting.head(10) # shows top 5 entries of the file

mass_shooting['Year'] = mass_shooting['Date'].dt.year     # seperates years from date 
year = mass_shooting['Year'].value_counts()           # counts values according to specific year
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))                                # decides size of plot
sns.barplot(year.index, year.values, alpha=0.7, color=color[3])
"""
Color
0 Blue
1 Orange
2 Green
3 Red
"""

plt.ylabel('Number of Attacks', fontsize=12)  # fontsize and label
plt.title('Attacks per Year', fontsize=18) # fontsize and label

def bar_datazoom_slider_a() -> Bar:
    c = (
        Bar()
        .add_xaxis(["Male", "Unknown", "Female", "Male/Female ", "M"])
        .add_yaxis("", [272, 21, 5, 4, 1])
        .set_global_opts(
            title_opts=opts.TitleOpts(title=""),
        )
    )
    return c

def bar_datazoom_slider_b() -> Bar:
    c = (
        Bar()
        .add_xaxis(['White American or European American', 'Black American or African American  ', 'Unknown  ',
       'Some other race', 'white',
       'Asian American  ', 'Asian  ',
       'Native American or Alaska Native',

        .set_global_opts(
            title_opts=opts.TitleOpts(title=""),
        )
    )
    return c


def bar_datazoom_slider_c() -> Bar:

from pyecharts.faker import Faker
from pyecharts import options as opts
from pyecharts.charts import Pie


# 
dff = pd.read_csv('own.csv')

# countryaverage firearms per 100 people
# 
dd= dff[['country','Average']]
dd1=dd.sort_values('Average',ascending=False)
dd2=dd1.head(21)


# 
dd3 =list(dd2.values)


def pie_scroll_legend() -> Pie:
    c = (
        Pie()
        .add(
            "",
            dd3,
            
            label_opts=opts.LabelOpts(is_show=False),
        )
        .set_global_opts(
            title_opts=opts.TitleOpts(title="",subtitle="100"),
            legend_opts=opts.LegendOpts(
                type_="scroll", pos_left="80%", orient="vertical"
            ),
        )
        .set_series_opts(label_opts=opts.LabelOpts(formatter="{b}: {c}"))
    )
    return c

pie_scroll_legend().render_notebook()

            [0.6, 'rgb(158,154,200)'],[0.8, 'rgb(117,107,177)'],[1.0, 'rgb(84,39,143)']]
